ty Kildare, Irland","Rathcoffey, County Kildare, Ireland":"Rathcoffey, County Kildare, Irland","Picton, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Picton, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"nl":{"1354–December 1422":"1354–december 1422","1354–1422":"1354–1422","1355–1390":"1355–1390","1370–Female":"1370–Overleden","1394–1435":"1394–1435","1375–1421":"1375–1421","1376–1435":"1376–1435","1335–1376":"1335–1376","1335–Female":"1335–Overleden","December 1422":"december 1422","before 1376":"vóór 1376","before 1353":"vóór 1353","1394":"1394","1370":"1370","abt 1375":"circa 1375","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1435":"1435","1335":"1335","1422":"1422","1421":"1421","1355":"1355","1354":"1354","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","about 1375":"circa 1375","about 1394":"circa 1394","Ireland":"Ierland","Wales":"Wales","England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","County Kildare, Ireland":"County Kildare, Ierland","Rathcoffey, County Kildare, Ireland":"Rathcoffey, County Kildare, Ierland","Picton, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Picton, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"en":{"1354–December 1422":"1354–December 1422","1354–1422":"1354–1422","1355–1390":"1355–1390","1370–Female":"1370–Deceased","1394–1435":"1394–1435","1375–1421":"1375–1421","1376–1435":"1376–1435","1335–1376":"1335–1376","1335–Female":"1335–Deceased","December 1422":"December 1422","before 1376":"before 1376","before 1353":"before 1353","1394":"1394","1370":"1370","abt 1375":"about 1375","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1435":"1435","1335":"1335","1422":"1422","1421":"1421","1355":"1355","1354":"1354","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","about 1375":"about 1375","about 1394":"about 1394","Ireland":"Ireland","Wales":"Wales","England":"England, United Kingdom","County Kildare, Ireland":"County Kildare, Ireland","Rathcoffey, County Kildare, Ireland":"Rathcoffey, County Kildare, Ireland","Picton, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Picton, Pembrokeshire, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wogan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh, English, and Irish (Dublin): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Guoccaun</i>, which derives from the ancestor of Modern Welsh <i>gogawn</i> ‘honour, glory’. In Middle Welsh it became <i>Gwogon</i> and <i>Gwogan</i> and was adopted as a surname by a south Pembrokeshire Anglo-Norman family in the normanized or Anglicized pronunciation <i>Wogan</i>. Compare   Cadogan  . In Ireland the name has been Gaelicized as <b>Úgán</b>.","History: A family of this name settled in County Kildare following the Anglo-Norman invasion of the 12th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ogan","meanings":["Irish: of Welsh origin, a variant of   Wogan  , found Gaelicized as <b>Úgán</b>."]},{"name":"Vogan","meanings":["Irish: of Welsh origin, a variant of   Wogan  ."]},{"name":"Cadogan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot.","Welsh (Pembrokeshire and Glamorgan) and Irish (of Welsh origin): from the Old Welsh personal name <i>Catgucaun</i>, <i>Catguocawn</i>, modernized as <i>Cadwgon</i>. It is composed of <i>cad</i> ‘battle’ + <i>gogawn</i> ‘honour, glory’. See also   Wogan  . The surname is stressed, like its Welsh original, on the penultimate syllable, hence its occasional development to   Duggan  .","Irish: from <b>Ó Ceadagáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Ceadagán</i>’."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning ‘darling’. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When David Wogan was born in 1354, in Wales, his father, John Wogan, was 20 and his mother, Isabel Landres, was 20. He married Anne Plunkett about 1375, in Wales. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in December 1422, at the age of 68."},"et":{"1354–December 1422":"1354–detsember 1422","1354–1422":"1354–1422","1355–1390":"1355–1390","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1394–1435":"1394–1435","1375–1421":"1375–1421","1376–1435":"1376–1435","1335–1376":"1335–1376","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","December 1422":"detsember 1422","before 1376":"enne 1376","before 1353":"enne 1353","1394":"1394","1370":"1370","abt 1375":"umbes 1375","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1435":"1435","1335":"1335","1422":"1422","1421":"1421","1355":"1355","1354":"1354","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","about 1375":"umbes 1375","about 1394":"umbes 1394","Ireland":"Iirimaa","Wales":"Wales","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","County Kildare, Ireland":"County Kildare, Iirimaa","Rathcoffey, County Kildare, Ireland":"Rathcoffey, County Kildare, Iirimaa","Picton, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Picton, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1354–December 1422":"1354–joulukuu 1422","1354–1422":"1354–1422","1355–1390":"1355–1390","1370–Female":"1370–Kuollut","1394–1435":"1394–1435","1375–1421":"1375–1421","1376–1435":"1376–1435","1335–1376":"1335–1376","1335–Female":"1335–Kuollut","December 1422":"joulukuu 1422","before 1376":"ennen vuotta 1376","before 1353":"ennen vuotta 1353","1394":"1394","1370":"1370","abt 1375":"noin 1375","1391":"1391","1390":"1390","1435":"1435","1335":"1335","1422":"1422","1421":"1421","1355":"1355","1354":"1354","1376":"1376","1375":"1375","about 1375":"noin 1375","about 1394":"noin 1394","Ireland":"Irlanti","Wales":"Wales","England":"